  "<i>Tetelestai</i> is not a cry of defeat but a declaration of completion. It answers the preceding verse: “Jesus, seeing that all things were now finished…” (19:28), and his prayer of the night before: “I accomplished the work which you have given me to do” (17:4). The work entrusted by the Father is carried to its end.",
  "Then John chooses his words: “he <span class='g'>gave up</span> his spirit” (19:30). Life is not torn from him: it is handed over. Jesus had announced it: “No one takes it away from me, but I lay it down by myself” (John 10:18). The cross is an offering, not merely an execution."],
  h3:"The blood and the water",
  s2c:["From the pierced side come “blood and water” (19:34), and John, as witness, solemnly insists on it. The blood: the offering and the covenant (Exodus 24:8). The water: life given, the rivers of living water promised (John 7:38) and the “spring opened for sin” of Zechariah 13:1. Christians very early recognized here their two signs of new life — the section The Offering will return to it."],
  deep:[
  ["Tetelestai, a word from receipts","The verb <i>teleô</i> means to bring to completion; receipts of the period use it in the sense of “paid”. Without reducing the cross to a commercial metaphor, the NT does assume the register of price: “you were bought with a price” (1 Corinthians 6:20), “redeemed… with precious blood, as of a lamb without blemish” (1 Peter 1:18-19)."],
  ["The sixth hour: an honest difficulty","Mark 15:25 places the crucifixion at the third hour; John 19:14 places the sentence “about the sixth”. Proposed solutions: different systems of counting hours, rounded approximations, or John's theological intention (the hour of the lambs). We display the difficulty instead of hiding it: that is this site's policy, and the details of the debate are in the reference dossier."],
  ["The hyssop, a discreet signature","Matthew and Mark mention a reed; John alone names hyssop — botanically frail for carrying a sponge, which is precisely why many read it as a theological signature: the instrument of the Passover blood (Exodus 12:22) reappears at the instant the Lamb dies. The evangelist writes for readers who know their Exodus."],
  ["The eyewitness","“He who has seen has testified, and his testimony is true” (19:35) — the same insistence in 21:24 and in 1 John 1:1 (“that which we have seen with our eyes… and our hands touched”). For the “A Bible worthy of trust” section: the Gospels present themselves as testimony, a genre that exposes itself to verification — not as myth."],
  ["“They will look on him whom they pierced”","Zechariah 12:10, quoted in 19:37, returns in Revelation 1:7: the word planted at Golgotha reopens the last book. And in Zechariah, it is God who speaks in the first person of “him whom they pierced” — one of the texts of our thread “One God — Father, Son, Spirit”."]],
